Now let’s start the full roadmap.

## Phase 0 – First 1–2 Months – Mindset + Setup (Start NOW)

### 1. Simple Mindset
- You are not late — you are in first year — most start in third year
- No zero days — even 30–45 min daily is good
- Compare only with yourself last month
- College exams important — keep CGPA >7.0
- Mistakes are okay — learn from them
- Small daily work = big future

### 2. Easy Tracking (Use Notebook or Google Sheet)
Write every week:
- Week number
- How many problems solved
- What project I worked on
- Hours studied
- One good thing I did
- One thing to improve

### 3. Make Accounts (Do in First Week)
- GitHub (username simple: yourname-ai or sanket-aiml)
- LinkedIn (headline: "B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | Learning Python & ML")
- LeetCode / CodeChef account
- Google account for Drive / Sheets

### 4. Daily Time Table (Choose One)
**Only 1 hour free:**
- 30 min Python / DSA
- 20 min watch video
- 10 min revise

**2–3 hours free:**
- 1 hour DSA / Python practice
- 1 hour project or ML video
- 30 min English / communication practice

### 5. Health First (Don’t Skip)
- Sleep 7 hours
- Walk 20–30 min daily
- Drink water
- No all-night study — brain needs rest

## Phase 1 – Months 1–6 (First Year – Build Base)

### 1. Learn Python Very Well (Most Important for AIML)
Python is language of AI / ML. Master it first.

**Step-by-Step What to Learn:**
1. Install Python + VS Code (1 day)
2. Print, input, variables, data types (int, float, str, bool)
3. If-else, loops (for, while)
4. Lists, tuples, dictionaries, sets
5. Functions (normal, lambda)
6. File reading/writing
7. Basic OOP (class, object, __init__)
8. Modules (import math, random, datetime)
9. Exception handling (try-except)
10. List comprehension

**Resources (Free & Easy):**
- CodeWithHarry Python (Hindi) – best for beginners
- Apna College Python playlist
- freeCodeCamp Python (English)
- Automate the Boring Stuff with Python (free book online)

**Goal:** Write small programs without seeing video (like calculator, guessing game)

### 2. Start Easy DSA in Python
DSA is important even for AI jobs (interviews ask)

**Platforms:**
- CodeChef (starters)
- LeetCode (easy problems)
- GeeksforGeeks practice

**First 6 months topics (easy only):**
- Patterns (stars, numbers)
- Basic math (prime, factorial, sum digits)
- Arrays / Lists (sum, max, reverse, rotate)
- Strings (palindrome, count vowels, reverse)
- Simple recursion (factorial, fibo)
- Basic searching & sorting

**Target:** 150–300 easy problems  
Do 4–7 problems per week — think first, don’t copy

### 3. First Small Projects (Use Python)
Do 4–6 small projects in first year.

Ideas:
1. Number Guessing Game
2. To-Do List (save in file)
3. Quiz Game (MCQ)
4. Student Marks Manager (add, show, average)
5. Simple Calculator with menu
6. Password Generator

**Rule:** Finish one project every 4–6 weeks. Put on GitHub.

### 4. Start Understanding AI / ML Basics
Watch easy videos — no deep math yet.

**What to Learn (Simple):**
- What is AI? (like Siri, ChatGPT)
- What is Machine Learning? (learn from data)
- Types: supervised, unsupervised
- What is data? (numbers, text, images)
- Simple libraries: numpy, pandas intro

**Resources:**
- Apna College AI playlist (Hindi)
- CodeWithHarry ML intro
- 3Blue1Brown Neural Network video (English, very beautiful)

**Goal:** Understand “ML = computer learns from examples”

## Phase 2 – Months 7–12 (End First Year to Mid Second Year)

### 1. DSA – Go to Medium Level Slowly
Now increase difficulty — but slowly.

**Topics:**
- Advanced arrays (Kadane, two pointers easy)
- Linked List basics (reverse, cycle)
- Stack & Queue simple
- Binary Search more problems
- Recursion medium (subsets, permutations easy)

**Target:** 400–600 total problems (250–400 medium)

**Tip:** Solve 5–8 problems per week — no hurry

### 2. Full Python for AI
- Numpy (arrays, math operations)
- Pandas (read CSV, clean data, group by)
- Matplotlib / Seaborn (simple charts)
- Scikit-learn intro (simple models)

**Resources:**
- Kaggle Python course (free)
- CampusX YouTube (Hindi ML)

### 3. First ML Projects
Do 3–5 simple ML projects.

Ideas:
1. Predict house price (simple linear regression)
2. Iris flower classification
3. Titanic survival prediction (Kaggle)
4. Spam email detector
5. Handwritten digit recognizer (MNIST)

**Where to get data:** Kaggle.com (free datasets)

**Goal:** Understand train-test split, accuracy, confusion matrix

### 4. GitHub & Deployment
- Make every project repo nice
- Deploy simple apps: Streamlit (very easy for ML)
- Example: deploy house price predictor online

## Phase 3 – Second Year – Become Strong in AIML

### 1. DSA – Medium Comfortable
- Trees basics (binary tree traversal)
- Graphs intro (BFS/DFS)
- Greedy & DP easy problems

**Target:** 600–900 total (400+ medium)

### 2. Deep into Machine Learning
- Supervised learning: regression, classification
- Unsupervised: clustering, PCA
- Evaluation metrics (accuracy, precision, recall, F1, ROC)
- Overfitting / underfitting
- Cross-validation

**Libraries:**
- Scikit-learn full
- TensorFlow / PyTorch intro

### 3. Deep Learning Basics
- What is neural network?
- Activation functions
- Loss functions
- Backpropagation simple
- CNN intro (image classification)

**Projects:**
- Image classification (cats vs dogs)
- Sentiment analysis (movie reviews)
- Simple chatbot

### 4. Good Projects for Resume
1. Movie Recommendation System
2. Face Mask Detector
3. Stock Price Prediction
4. Plant Disease Detection
5. Chatbot with API

**Deploy:** Streamlit / Hugging Face Spaces / Vercel

## Phase 4 – Internship & Placement Prep (End Second Year)

- Apply on Internshala, LinkedIn, AngelList
- Make resume: projects + GitHub + DSA count
- Practice explaining projects
- Mock interviews (friends / YouTube)

**Target:** 1 internship in summer 2027 (AI/ML/Data role)

## End of Second Year Checklist
- [ ] Python + Numpy/Pandas comfortable
- [ ] 600–900 DSA problems
- [ ] 10–15 good projects (deployed)
- [ ] Basic ML models built
- [ ] GitHub 150+ commits
- [ ] 30–70 applications sent
- [ ] CGPA safe

## Mistakes to Avoid
- Only watch videos — not code
- Jumping libraries without basics
- No deployment — show live work
- Skipping DSA — interviews ask
- Burnout — take rest

